l Vlaicu (Hunedoara Region) -- tRevolution in Bits and Pieces: Collectivization in Southern Romania (Craiova Region) -- tPersuasion Techniques and Community Reactions in Corund (the Hungarian Autonomous Region) -- t“Never Leave ‘til Tomorrow What You Can Do Today!”* A Case Study of a Model Collective Farm: “New Life” Sântana (Arad Region) -- t“Here in Reviga, There Was Nobody to Wage the Class Struggle”: Collectivization in Reviga, Bărăgan Plain (Bucharest Region) -- tOne Step Back, Two Steps Forward: Institutionalizing the Party-State and Collective Property in Two Romanian Villages (Galaţi Region) -- tConclusions -- tAnnexes -- tGeneral Bibliography on the Collectivization of Agriculture in Romania -- tThe Communist Take-Over and Land Collectivization in Romania: Chronology of Events, 1945–1962 -- tTable of Research Villages -- tMaps -- tMap 1: Administrative division of Romania, 1950 -- tMap 2: Administrative division of Romania, 1952 -- tMap 3: Administrative division of Romania, 1960 -- tMap 4: List of Research Villages -- tList of Abbreviations -- tGlossary of Terms -- tAuthors -- tPhoto Credits -- tIndex -- tPhotos0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe subject matter of the volume is part of larger research agenda on the process of land collectivization in the former communist camp, focusing on state, identity and property. The main innovation of the volume is to apply recent interdisciplinary approaches to the study of the collectivization process, asking what types of new peasant-state relations it formed and how it transformed notions of self, persons, and things (such as land). The project conceived of changes in the system of ownership as causing changes in the identity and attitude of people; similarly, it regarded the study of personal identities as essential for understanding changes in the system of ownership. This perspective is rare in the area-studies approaches to the topic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAgriculture, Collectivization, Communism, Economic history, Romania, Transylvania.1 aBodó, Julianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChelcea, Liviu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobrincu, Dorin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobrincu, Dorin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoina, Călin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIordachi, Constantin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIordachi, Constantin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKligman, Gail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevy, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLăţea, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOláh, Sándor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOprea, Marius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStan, Răzvan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStewart, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStoica, Cătălin Augustin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerdery, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVultur, Smaranda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aŢârău, Virgiliu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral Europ